Thanks a lot to Mark for help with ID and access to a powerful scope!

Observation Details: Bird seen at the end of sundown so visibility was somewhat poor. Still, moderately confident of the ID of a Phalarope sp: very white neck seen clearly, very pointy bill, constant erratic movement and large head bobbing motions. ID of Wilson's Phalarope based on the following: clean white underparts; pale legs (couldn't say color, just that they were pale); bill a bit longer than head width; likely the best ID characteristic was that this bird was obviously taller than a spotted sandpiper that was next to the bird (~5-10m away) in the same plane of view. Shined a floodlight on the rock outcrop once visibility became too poor, which immediately scared up a total of 5 birds (1 Ruddy Turnstone, 1 Spotted Sandpiper, 2 previously unseen birds, and this bird). A mixture of calls made it too difficult to pick out the sound made by this bird. The low lighting (1/8 of a second shutter speed used) and erratic behavior of the bird made it very difficult to get a shot in focus. We are in this spot for another week and will recheck daily for the bird

Observation Details: Seen at the end of Cape Raven Trail near L'anse Aux Meadows. On the mossy and rocky tundra at the lookout over the bay on Cape Raven Hill. Two independent identifications by two in party. Clear grey head and clean transition between head and brown/reddish wings. Clear grey body between end of wings and tail. Dark tail, but not black. Closer to dark brown. Pale chest with thrush-like spots, appeared clustered, resembling lines. Faint line by eye. Seen hopping on the tundra, foraging for what appeared to be berries. Solitary. 7 robins counted in the surrounding area, but bird was not seen directly associating with robins. Exhibited clear, deliberate, hopping/stomping behavior between short bouts of foraging. Almost like the bird was pressing down the spongy moss to get at berries. Fanned tail and hit the ground with it after landing from hops/very short flights during foraging. Flew off over a small rocky outcrop and was lost from sight near a patch of spruce woods. Too windy to obtain a photo with cellphone through binoculars. *Sadly* no camera on hand. Also, spotty internet so this is first opportunity I have to upload this observation, approximately 28h after the observation.
